summary.seg: This manuscript, unusually, contains almost the entire New Testament, combining the normal content of a Gospel book and an Acts and Epistles book. Each of the Epistles is preceded by a standard introductory hypothesis, describing the circumstances of its composition. The manuscript probably dates to the 13th century, but the text is significant for a copy of such late date, containing numerous unusual variant readings, and it has been used as a witness for many New Testament editions.

The very black ink used by the copyists of the main text suggests that the manuscript may have been produced in the Levant, or in Cyprus. This probability is reinforced by the presence of a sequence of Armenian quire signatures, indicating that the manuscript was rebound at some point by an Armenian-speaker, which would be consistent with its presence in these same regions.

The manuscript appears to have been produced in separate blocks, one comprising the Gospels and the other the Acts and Epistles. It may indeed have been originally intended as two separate volumes, whether or not they were ever in fact bound separately, or produced originally as an Acts and Epistles book which was then expanded by the addition of the Gospels, though the commonalities of script and decoration indicate that the production of all parts of the manuscript was closely associated.

The beginning of the Acts of the Apostles (f. 135r) marks the beginning of the original sequence of quire signatures, which starts with the number 1, omitting the first eighteen quires. This indicates that the section beginning with Acts was originally produced separately from that containing the Gospels, and may well have been meant to be bound separately. This section would not have been a complete Acts and Epistles book, however, as the sequence of signatures does not cover the last four quires, which contain the whole of the last seven Epistles. That this was no chance omission is indicated by the fact that this change not only comes at a clean break between biblical books, but is preceded by a shortened quire, of only four folios rather than the usual eight. The same applies to the point where the quire signatures begin, which is preceded by a quire of only six folios. These quires of reduced length seemingly each marked the end of an allocation of work. The scribe could not simply continue by copying the next book in the same quire, as that book and those following it had either already been produced or had been assigned to someone else to copy. The fact that the beginning of Acts is also accompanied by a change of hands suggests that the different portions of work were assigned to the two scribes, Hand A taking the Gospels and the last few Epistles and Hand B the rest, and that this division of labour accounts for the physical division. However, the abrupt return of Hand A after only a dozen folios (f. 147v, line 5) shows that, if so, this plan did not last long, as Hand A was required to take over Hand B's assignment as well.

The original production plan was certainly not fulfilled with regard to decoration. The manuscript appears to have been prepared for miniatures of each author, which were never added. This is suggested by the presence of empty rectangular borders during the Epistles, each appearing early in the work of the four authors of letters (f. 179v James; f. 190r 2 Peter; f. 194r 1 John; f. 200v Jude; f. 203r Romans (i.e. Paul)). This in turn suggests that the blank folios found between the different Gospels may have been set aside for full-page miniatures, including portraits of the Evangelists. Such decorations never having been added, the space between the Gospels was later filled with summary lection listings and a list of the Epistles by a less elegant and probably less professional hand than the main copyists (ff. v verso-vi verso, 38v, 61v-62v, 132v-134v).

msItem.title: Gospels, Act and Epistles book
msItem.note: Gregory-Aland 440; Von Soden δ 260 (e: I'; ap: Ib2); Scrivener Evan. 440.
msItem.filiation: The manuscript contains significant variant readings and has been used in the Nestle-Aland, Bover-O'Callaghan, UBS, Merk, Vogels, BFBS, Souter and Huck-Greeven editions.

support.material: Parchment (FHHF), of medium thickness and good quality.

supportDesc.foliation: The manuscript is foliated with the numbers [a-b] + i-vi, 1-288 + [c-d] in pencil in Arabic and Roman numerals, recto, upper right.

collation.p: The manuscript consists of 38 quires, of which one is a binion, two are ternia and the rest quaternia.

signatures.p: There are orignal quire signatures in red ink, in Greek numerals, on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right. This sequence always omitted the first 18 quires, since it begins with the number 1 at the start of Quire 19 (f. 135r), and perhaps also omitted the last 4 quires, which also lack these signatures. They appear on quires 19-34 (αʹ-ιϛʹ). They are occasionally slightly ornamented (e.g. ff. 199r, 207r).

A sequence of signatures in Armenian numerals, in black ink, has been placed on the first folio of each quire, recto, lower centre, and on the last folio of each quire, verso, lower centre. They appear on quires 2-38, beginning with the number 2. They are surrounded by simple ornament.
Modern quire signatures in Arabic numerals, in pencil, have been added to the first folio of each quire, recto, lower right.

supportDesc.condition: There is mild discoloration, more significant in the outermost folios, mild water damage to a few of the outer folios (ff. i recto-vi verso, 286v-288v) and occasional traces of dirt. There are occasional small tears to the edges of the leaves (e.g. ff. vi, 199), and some pest damage to the outermost leaves (ff. i, 278-288). The leaves are slightly cockled, and sometimes carry a horizontal crease. Text on f. 38v has been lost to fading.

layoutDesc.layout:
A single column of 28-30 lines. 122 92
Pricking sometimes survives on all three edges, but some has been lost to cropping. Ruled in hardpoint, system Leroy 1, type Leroy 32C1. Text hangs from the lines. The ruling is often very faint. Text preceding a punctuation mark, ranging in length from part of a word to a few words, is often written below the last line of text on a page, rather than carry the phrase on into the next page. The text at the end of each Gospel and of some Epistles is arranged in decorative patterns. The later summary lectionary text is written in a single column of 19-25 lines, without ruling.

handNote.p: ff. i recto-v verso, 1r-38r, 31r-61v, 63r-132r, 147v, line 5-f. 288v Most of the main text has been copied by Hand A in a calligraphic mixed minuscule script, with slightly variable slant but on average upright, in black ink. There is moderate variation in letter size, frequent flourishing of tails into the margins, and very numerous and elaborate ligatures.

Syllabic abbreviations and superscript word endings usually appear only at the end of lines, but occasionally elsewhere. Breathings are round and mute iota is usually absent, but very occasionally appears both adscript and subscript. There is decorative use of the double dot, and accentuation of all nomina sacra. The double grave accent is in use.

There are inclusions of letters within omicron. Distinctive letter-forms include a curving zeta opening to the right and resembling majuscule epsilon, extremely small majuscule eta, minuscule kappa with the ascender curved over to the right, majuscule lambda with its right-hand descender hooked back to the left, and minuscule nu with a minimal descender. The abbreviation of καὶ is sometimes used as part of a longer word.
Punctuation used includes the lower, middle and upper points, lower, middle and upper commas, question mark and full stop.
This hand has also provided the rubric and canon table text, in red ink in a similar style.

ff. 135r-147v, line 4 The early part of the Gospel of Luke has been copied by Hand B, as part of the same original programme of work, in a mixed minuscule script with very square letter-forms, slanting to the right, with moderate variation in letter size and some flourishing of tails into the margins.
Breathings are round or occasionally angular and elongated, and mute iota is absent, with decorative use of the double dot and accentuation of all nomina sacra. The double grave accent is in use.
Punctuation used includes the upper and middle points, lower and middle commas, question mark and full stop.

ff. v verso-vi verso, 38v, 61v-62v, 132v-134v Summary lection listings and a list of the Epistles have been added by Hand C, in a slightly informal mixed minuscule script, slanting slightly to the right, in pale brown ink. There is modest variation in letter size
Breathings are round or half-angular and mute iota is absent, with accentuation of all nomina sacra. Use of the double dot is functional only.

decoNote.p: Gospels and Acts are preceded by rectangular headpieces with vegetative ornament, in red ink:-

The beginning of the Epistles (f. 180r) is preceded by the slightly decorated boundary markings for another such headpiece, but the ornament within it and at the corners (for which gaps were left) was not added. These were supplied by a later hand in black ink.

Vignettes in red and black ink, with animal heads or occasionally vegetative ornament at their terminals, mark the end of each Gospel (e.g. ff. 338r, 102v), and the end of some Epistles or hypotheses and the beginning of the next (e.g. ff. 258v-259r, 263v-264r).

decoDesc.decoNote: The canon tables (ff. i recto-v recto) have decorative surrounds in red ink, with architectural and vegetative ornament.

decoNote.p: The text of each book or hypothesis begins with a relatively small ornamented major initial in red ink, in the same style as the headpieces. That for Matthew (f. 1r) is more ornate than the others, in the same style as the accompanying headpiece. Minor initials in red ink frequently appear at the beginning of lines.

decoDesc.decoNote: Line-fillers in red and black ink, with vegetative terminals, accompany the end or beginning of some Epistles and hypotheses (e.g. ff. 272r, 276v-277r).

decoNote.p: Rectangular boundaries for miniatures, presumably author portraits, have been marked out preceding one Epistle by each writer, but these have never been added:-

From this it may be conjectured that the pages left blank between books among the Gospels and Acts (ff. v verso-vi verso, 38v, 62r-62v, 132v-134v) were originally intended for larger miniatures, including Evangelist portraits, but that these two were never added, leaving the space free for Hand C to fill them with text at a later date.

additions.p: As part of the original production of the manuscript, Hands A and B have added marginal κεφάλαιον (chapter) numbers and τίτλοι (titles), Ammonian section numbers for the Gospels, and lection notes, and have placed ἀρχὴ and τέλος marks indicating the beginning and end of lections, in spaces left blank for the purpose in the text. Hand B has also added marginal quotation marks for Old Testament citations.
Occasional notes on lections have been added by various later hands (e.g. ff. 28r, 51v, 270v).

An ownership note has been added on f. i recto by the hieromonachos Makarios: Ἐτοῦτω τῶ τετραβάγγελω ἡπάρχη ἐμοῦ Μακαρίου ἰἐρομονάχου, καὶ ἦτης τῶ πάρη..ας εχηται ἀρᾶς τῶν τρηακοσίων δέκα καὶ οκτῶ θεοφόρων πατέρων ἀμήν. A note in an earlier hand on f. 288v may also be an ownership note, but is faded and substantially illegible.
A Latin hand, in black ink, has added modern chapter and verse numbers in runinng headers, and noted the content of the manuscript on f. 1r.

binding.p: Binding by W.H. Smith and Son Ltd in London, according to a note on the left pastedown. Quarter leather, with marbled paper covering over millboards and plain pastedowns. The classmark and the title Novum Testamentum Graecum are tooled in gold on the spine. The edges have been painted red, but only limited traces remain.

physDesc.accMat: Two scraps of leather from an older binding, bearing portions of the current shelfmark, have been pasted inside the left board.

history.origin: The use of very black ink and the later addition of Armenian quire signatures suggest that the manuscript was produced in Cyprus or the Levant. The characteristics of the script suggest that it was copied in the 13th century.
history.provenance: Owned by the hieromonachos Makarios Makarios , probably in the 17th or 18th century.
history.acquisition: Possibly presented in 1715 by George I George I, King of Great Britain, 1660-1727 , as part of the collection of John Moore (b. 1646, d. 1714), bishop of Ely Moore, John, 1646-1714 . This is suggested by the presence inside the left board of the bookplate used for this collection. However, this bookplate was sometimes incorrectly placed in manuscripts which did not belong to this collection, and this manuscript is not recorded as part of it in Bernard, Catalogi librorum manuscriptorum Angliæ et Hiberniæ (1697), nor in the handwritten supplementary list of Moore’s manuscripts, now MS Oo.7.50(2), compiled by Thomas Tanner Tanner, Thomas, 1674-1735 .
